	<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">CESM Simulations</h2>

	<p class="mb-4">
	We performed fully-coupled simulations using the 
	<a class="cactus-link inline-block"
		href="https://www.cesm.ucar.edu/"
		rel="noreferrer"
		target="_blank">Community Earth System Model</a>
	(CESM1.0.4). First, we extended Manabe's original \( CO_2 \) range to systematically 
	explore warm and cold climate states, going all the way from \(0.35\times CO_2 \) up to \(16\times CO_2  \). Second, we 
	greatly extended the integration length beyond other studies. To date, we have produced more than 150,000 years of 
	fully-coupled climate model output from these simulations, with several individual experiments approaching 20,000 years.
	This provides us with a unique model laboratory to study equilibrium climate effects: not only is the top of the 
	atmosphere equilibrated, but ideal age tracer is stabilising in the deep ocean in several experiments (more on this later). 
	</p>

	<h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-2">What we found</h2>

	<p class="mb-4">
	Similar to previous studies, we found that the AMOC rapidly collapses into a weaker state in response to abrupt global 
	warming. Also similar to previous studies, the AMOC recovers (\( 2\times CO_2 \); 850 years) and quadrupling (\( 4\times 
	CO_2 \); 3,500 years).
	</p>

	<p class="mb-4">
	However, our work using this model has revealed a far richer array of dynamics in the GMOC. For instance, during equilibration
	to an abrupt (\( 4\times CO_2 \)), we observed the spontaneous activation of the 
	<a class="cactus-link inline-block"
		href="https://doi.org/10.1175/JCLI-D-23-0393.1"
		rel="noreferrer"
		target="_blank">Pacific Meridional Overturning Circulation</a>
	(PMOC), which is not present in the present-day climate. 
	</p>

	<p class="mb-4">
	In another set of experiments with \(CO_2\) between \(0.5\times\) and \(0.56\times\)
	the pre-industrial, we observe spontaneous
	<a class="cactus-link inline-block"
		href="https://doi.org/10.1175/JCLI-D-24-0377.1"
		rel="noreferrer"
		target="_blank">Dansgaard-Oeschger-like Events</a>
	closely resembling the millennial-scale variability observed in the paleoclimate record.
	</p>

	<p class="mb-4">
	An even more exotic transition to a state characterised by millennial-scale variability driven in the 
	Southern Ocean is observed in several experiments between (\( \approx1.95-2\times CO_2 \)).
	</p>

	<p class="mb-4">
	Other interesting topics that we've approached with these experiments include equilibrium climate sensitivity (with
	<a class="cactus-link inline-block"
